  "key_insights": {
    "shock_characteristics": "Oil price spike (143%) is reflationary, not demand-driven. Administered price rigidity in fuel creates large inflation shock despite moderate GDP impact.",
    "petronas_paradox": "Despite massive crude spike, Petronas profit gains are modest because Malaysia oil production is declining (depletion). Cumulative 8-qtr profit RM422bn but Brent at baseline would yield ~RM360bn. Windfall only RM62bn (17% increase).",
    "fiscal_tension": "Government enjoys temporary fiscal surplus 2026-Q3 2027 due to PITA windfall. But structural deficit -3%+ reasserts once oil prices normalize and Petronas profits revert. Windfall must be spent wisely (debt reduction, not recurring commitments).",
    "inflation_stickiness": "Headline CPI reaches 25.46% while core inflation starts at 3.88% in Q2 2026, rises above 4% by Q3 2026, and exceeds 6% by late 2027. Administered prices account for about 21pp of the initial shock, but second-round and import-cost effects keep inflation elevated through 2028.",
    "labor_market_resilience": "Okun coefficient 0.45 implies unemployment remains broadly stable in this run, ending slightly below baseline at 3.37% versus 3.40%. Reality could still be worse if the E&E sector (38% of exports) adjusts faster than the model assumes; sensitivity test: elasticity 0.8 → unemployment 4.0-4.2%.",
    "household_stress": "Real wage growth -24% in Q2 2026. Household debt rises to 88.6% of GDP. Mortgage rates +50bps create debt service stress. Default risk elevated 2-3 years post-shock if housing market weakens.",
    "current_account_miracle": "Exceptional 8%+ of GDP surplus is driven by the oil/gas export price surge. It narrows steadily as oil normalizes, but is still 6.6% of GDP by Q1 2028, so this scenario does not return to a 1-2% surplus within the 8-quarter horizon.",
    "exchange_rate_managed": "REER depreciates -7.85% due to capital outflows and currency pressure. BNM intervention assumed at ~USD30bn; preserves stability. Could deteriorate to -15% if war extended and confidence collapses.",
    "policy_imperative": "Fuel subsidy reform essential but politically difficult. Government must use Petronas windfall for one-time transfers and debt reduction, not recurring spending expansion. OPR hike to 3.50% correct to anchor expectations."
  },
  "model_sources": {
